The root cause of the null dereference is that `compare_handler` is called with `func` potentially being `NULL` (as returned by `get_handler(signum)`), but `compare_handler` does not check for this before calling `PyLong_CheckExact(func)`, which dereferences the pointer.

**Patch plan:**
- Add a null check for `func` at the start of `compare_handler`.
- If `func` is `NULL`, return 0 (not equal).

This will prevent the null dereference in all call sites.

Here is the patch:
```diff
--- a/Modules/signalmodule.c
+++ b/Modules/signalmodule.c
@@ -182,7 +182,11 @@
 static inline int
 compare_handler(PyObject *func, PyObject *dfl_ign_handler)
 {
-    assert(PyLong_CheckExact(dfl_ign_handler));
-    if (!PyLong_CheckExact(func)) {
-        return 0;
-    }
-    // Assume that comparison of two PyLong objects will never fail.
-    return PyObject_RichCompareBool(func, dfl_ign_handler, Py_EQ) == 1;
+    assert(PyLong_CheckExact(dfl_ign_handler));
+    if (func == NULL) {
+        return 0;
+    }
+    if (!PyLong_CheckExact(func)) {
+        return 0;
+    }
+    // Assume that comparison of two PyLong objects will never fail.
+    return PyObject_RichCompareBool(func, dfl_ign_handler, Py_EQ) == 1;
 }
```
